This paper deals with deep convolutional neural networks and their computational efficiency, which are topics typically covered in the computer vision (cs.CV) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. The paper also introduces a reinforcement learning approach to dynamically choose which layers of a network to execute during inference, which falls under the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Additionally, the paper uses residual networks (ResNets), which are a popular architecture in computer vision, and explores their robustness to layer dropping, which could be relevant to the neural networks (cs.NE) sub-category. Finally, the paper evaluates its approach on image recognition tasks, which could be relevant to the natural language processing (cs.CL) sub-category.
